Disk Forensics > [T5]: File and Directory Tracking

(4) $I30 INDX 

NTFS Index Attributes, also known as $I30, is another artifact used by Windows NTFS filesystems to track which files are in which directories. Each time you update a folder content (i.e., delete a file), this index will be updated to reflect new changes. However, it may keep a track record of deleted files, even if securely wiped. The $I30 is very effective if you want to prove the existence of a particular file on the system, even if it does not exist anymore.

Since $I30 keeps track of the structure of all files and directories on the system, each directory on an NTFS drive will include its $I30 file.

 

$I30 - (zoom in)

You can use the "MFTEcmd" or "INDXRipper" tool to parse a $I30 file and produce a CSV file ready for "TimeLine Explorer."

Timeline Explorer - (zoom in)

  1. File or directory path
  2. Flags (Hidden, system file, directory)
  3. File size.
  4. Creation time. The rest of the timestamps (Modified, Access) are next to the "Creation time" column
